com.ojcoleman.europa.configurable

Class PrototypeBase

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ojcoleman.europa.configurable.Observable
      • com.ojcoleman.europa.configurable.ConfigurableBase
        • com.ojcoleman.europa.configurable.PrototypeBase
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Stringable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Allele, Gene, Genotype, Individual, ParametrisedNeuralNetwork, Species

    public abstract class PrototypeBase
extends ConfigurableBase

    In Europa the class to use for many types of object is determined at run-time, for example the class to use for an individual or a genotype. If many of these objects must be instantiated throughout a run then it becomes very inefficient to do this via Java's Reflection API. The quickest method is to use object cloning methods, followed by copy constructors (see this and this). However a good argument can be made that Java's clone should be avoided. Additionally the clone approach is less flexible than the copy constructor approach, for example setting the value of final fields to a new value in the copy is impossible. Thus Prototype employs the copy constructor approach to create new instances.

    Because Prototype extends ConfigurableBase, if a Prototype class contains fields with Parameter annotations then the values for those fields will be automatically set from the values supplied in the JsonObject when the Prototype is instantiated. This is described in more detail in the class documentation for ConfigurableBase.

    One or more copy constructors must be implemented, optionally accepting additional parameters besides the prototype object to copy. This allows creating new instances with some values that should be unique to that instance. For example, copies of an Allele prototype can be created which have a different value for the Allele.gene field (which is final and so could not be set after instantiating the copy instance).

    New instances of prototypes may be created with newInstance(Object...).

    All sub-classes must:

    • have a constructor that accepts a JsonObject as its only parameter and which calls the super-class's JsonObject constructor,
    • implement one or more copy constructors, optionally accepting additional parameters besides the prototype object to copy.
    Example: public Allele(Configuration config) { super(config); } public Allele(Allele allele, Gene gene) { super(allele); this.gene = gene; }

    When newInstance(Object...) is first called with a particular list of parameter types it uses Java's Reflection API to find the copy constructor matching those parameter types. It then calls AccessibleObject.setAccessible(boolean) on the Constructor in order to avoid future security checks in order to improve performance when invoking the constructor. A reference to the Constructor is cached to avoid determining the correct constructor for the given parameter types in future calls. Finally Constructor.newInstance(Object...) is called to create the new instance of the prototype.

    The approach taken by this class represents a trade-off between flexibility (accepting any number arguments when creating new instances and allowing setting the value of final fields of new instances), speed (avoiding Reflection mechanisms as much as possible), and ease of use (for example not requiring sub-classes to have methods or constructors accepting arbitrary numbers of Object parameters via a varargs parameter or similar).

    Author:
    O. J. Coleman

    • Constructor Detail

      • PrototypeBase

        public PrototypeBase(Configuration config)
        Constructor to initialise the prototype object from which all other instances should be copied. Sub-classes must implement a constructor accepting the same parameters and call super(config). Overriding implementations of this constructor should return after calling super() if null is provided (null is used to create dummy instances when printing the available default configuration options).
        Parameters:
        config - The configuration for this ConfigurableBase.

      • PrototypeBase

        public PrototypeBase(PrototypeBase prototype)

        Copy constructor to create a copy of the given prototype object. All sub-classes must implement their own copy constructor, calling the super-class copy constructor.

        This should generally be a "deep" copy, where every object reference is replaced by a deep copy of the referenced object recursively as necessary. However some object reference fields may be copied by reference rather than being deep copied, for example if the class references objects which should be shared with other instances.

        Note: Fields annotated with Prototype will be copied by reference automatically. If this is not desired for a specific field then it's value can be set to something else after calling super().

    • Method Detail

      • newInstance

        public <T extends PrototypeBase> T newInstance(java.lang.Object... newInstanceParameters)
        Returns a new instance of this prototype. Care must be taken to ensure that there is a matching copy constructor for this prototype class, that is, a constructor that accepts an instance of this class followed by the newInstanceParameters given.
        Parameters:
        newInstanceParameters - The parameters to pass to the copy constructor (besides the prototype object itself).
        Throws:
        NewInstanceConstructorException - If the required constructor exists but is not accessible (for example is private), or the constructor throws an exception, or some other Java reflective error occurred.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If this prototype class does not declare a copy constructor accepting the required parameters.
